Revealed comparative advantage and network centrality

Sergej Kaiser

1/26/2017

Introduction

Motivation

  • IPF: goods are produced in several stages in multiple countries.
  • Literature shows large extent of international product fragmentation.
  • Empirical findings:
    • Distribution of who produces for whom looks different for VAT than EXGR.
    • Volume of trade flows changes significantly under VAT compared to EXGR.

IPF and RCA

  • Ricardo: Country CA in production and exporting of goods for which rel. lower production cost compared to trade partners.
  • Before IPF: EXGR good measure of domestic contribution of factors & inputs.
  • With IPF: EXGR include foreign contributions to rel. production costs.
  • Pattern of specialization of countries may be sensitive to looking at VAT instead of EXGR.
  • 1st objective: Quantify the degree of divergence betweeen RCA on the basis of EXGR and VAT.

Importance of Countries - Shock propagation

  • 2nd Objective: Assess contribution of different countries to the propagation of shocks in the ITN.
  • Previous research on the basis of gross trade flows.
  • Given extent of IPF, important to construct this analysis with VAT.
  • Theoretical measure: Follow Acemoglu et al. (2012) - eigenvector centrality.
  • For the sake of time, I omit details about methodology.
  • Glad to answer questions about methodology at later point.

Data

  • TiVA: 61 countries. Including: OECD, EU 28, G20 and most of East and South-East Asian and some South American countries.

  • WiOD: 41 countires. Including: EU 27 and 14 other major countries.

  • Both cover: primary, manufacturing and service industries according to the ISIC Rev. 3.1.

Proceed

  • 1st: Use theoretical sound approach extract pattern of relative sectoral costs on the basis of EXGR and VAT.
    • Check whether pattern of rel. sectoral costs is unchanged for total cost, or cost on the basis of domestic supply chain (BVAT), or domestic production factors (FVAT).
  • 2nd: Assess whether importance of countries is similar across sectoral networks.

Main Results

Revealed comparative advantage

  • Foreign supply chain does not modify pattern of specialization while domestic supply chain does matter for a subset of countries. See: Germany
    & Full set of countries

  • Pattern of RCA on the basis of EXGR:
    • Captures contribution of domestic supply chain.
    • Caputres less well the pattern of RCA the basis of factor content of trade.

  • 2nd result RCA: VA data should be regarded with caution for developing countries.

Importance of Countries - Shock propagation

  • Total value-added: core-periphery structure.
  • Sectoral value-added: Variability in countries’ importance .
  • Relative terms ranking of centrality maps closely into ranking of RCA for most countires.

RCA and Network centrality

Conclusion

  • Given extent of IPF, analysed the degree of divergence betweeen RCA on the basis of EXGR and VAT.
  • Results indicate:
  • Pattern of RCA on the basis of EXGR:
    1. Captures contribution of domestic supply chain.
    2. Caputres less well the pattern of RCA the basis of factor content of trade.
  • 2nd result RCA: VA data should be regarded with caution for developing countries.

  • Analysed whether importance of countries is similar across sectoral networks on the basis of VAT.
  • Findings:
    1. Sectoral value-added: Variability in countries’ importance
    2. Relative terms ranking of centrality maps closely into ranking of RCA for most countries.
